## Validation gates

This document defines the technical gates a completed compiler or documentation
slice must pass.

The required final gate depends on whether the slice changes implementation or
is strictly documentation-only.

### Compiler invocation

Use an up-to-date release build of the compiler when one is available. The
`bean` command in PATH is the usual direct form:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    bean check docs
    bean build docs --release
]

If a suitable release build is not available, run the same operations through
Cargo from the repository root:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    cargo run --quiet -- check docs
    cargo run --quiet -- build docs --release
]

### Choose the final gate by scope

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Slice**]
        [: **Required final gate**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Code-bearing or mixed change]
        [: `just validate`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Strictly documentation-only change]
        [: `bean build docs --release` or the equivalent Cargo invocation]
    ]
]

The `justfile` is the executable authority for the full code-bearing gate.

### Code-bearing final gate

A slice is code-bearing if it changes Rust, compiler or build-system sources,
libraries, tests, benchmarks, manifests, scripts, configuration or any other
non-documentation implementation file.

Before declaring a non-trivial code-bearing slice complete, run:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    just validate
]

#### What just validate runs

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Gate**]
        [: **Current command**]
        [: **Purpose**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Cross-target Clippy]
        [: `just ci-clippy`]
        [: Native, Linux x64 and Windows x64 linting with warnings denied]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Rust unit tests]
        [: `cargo test --quiet -- --format terse`]
        [: Rust unit and subsystem tests]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Compiler integration tests]
        [: `cargo run --quiet -- tests`]
        [: End-to-end compiler cases]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Documentation check]
        [: `cargo run --quiet -- check docs`]
        [: Beanstalk docs-source checking inside the full gate]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Benchmark sanity check]
        [: `cargo run --package xtask --bin xtask -- bench-check`]
        [: Non-recording performance sanity check]
    ]
]

- `ci-clippy` uses the pinned Rust toolchain configured in the `justfile`.
- Warnings are denied.
- It checks the native host, Linux x64 and Windows x64 targets.
- Benchmark checking must not update tracked benchmark history.

### Documentation-only release-build gate

A slice is documentation-only only when every modified file is documentation
source or generated documentation.

Allowed examples include:

- files under `docs/**`
- an explicitly requested root documentation file such as `README.md`,
  `CONTRIBUTING.md` or `AGENTS.md`
- generated files under `docs/release/**`

A documentation-only slice must not change Rust, tests, libraries, build
configuration, manifests, scripts, benchmark code or fixtures, compiler
configuration or other executable project sources.

For a strictly documentation-only slice, run one documentation release build
using a current compiler.

The direct release-binary form is:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    bean build docs --release
]

If no suitable release build is available, use
`cargo run --quiet -- build docs --release` instead.

Then:

- inspect every changed route
- inspect the generated diff
- verify links, tables and code examples
- confirm generated output came from source changes
- confirm the changed-file list contains documentation only.

Do not additionally run `just validate`, Clippy, unit tests, integration tests
or benchmark checks for a documentation-only slice. A Cargo invocation of the
compiler is an alternative way to run the same documentation gate, not an
extra gate.

If any non-documentation file changed, the documentation-only exception does
not apply. Use the full code-bearing gate.

### Fast iteration commands

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Task**]
        [: **Command**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Unit-test iteration]
        [: `cargo test --quiet -- --format terse`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Integration iteration]
        [: `bean tests`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Clippy iteration]
        [: `just ci-clippy`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Docs-source iteration]
        [: `bean check docs`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Benchmark sanity]
        [: `just bench-check`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Documentation release-build iteration]
        [: `bean build docs --release`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Complete code-bearing gate]
        [: `just validate`]
    ]
]

Passing one targeted command does not imply a code-bearing slice passes the
complete gate.

### Formatting

- Run `cargo fmt` when Rust files changed.
- `just validate` does not currently format source automatically.
- Do not solve formatting failures through lint suppression.
- Documentation-only changes do not require Rust formatting.

The `ship` recipe formats before validation, while `validate` itself does not.

### Generated documentation

Do not edit files under `docs/release/**` directly.

The documentation release build is:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    bean build docs --release
]

A generated diff must result from documentation source changes, not manual HTML
edits.

### Manual architecture audits

When a code-bearing slice changes stage ownership, frontend boundaries, HIR,
diagnostics, types or backend handoff, perform a manual architecture audit in
addition to the automated gate.

Audit that:

- stage ownership remains narrow
- AST and HIR type representation still respect `TypeEnvironment` and `TypeId`
- user-facing failures use `CompilerDiagnostic`
- internal and infrastructure failures use `CompilerError`
- no obsolete API or duplicated path remains
- no backend reparses source syntax
- no analysis mutates HIR when its contract is side-table based
- comments and documentation name the current owner
- no compatibility shim preserves an obsolete path

This full architecture audit is not required for a prose-only documentation
change.

### Progress-matrix review

Review the progress matrix whenever behavior, support, rejection, backend
coverage or test coverage changes.

Update it when current status changed. Do not make a meaningless edit for a
pure refactor or prose-only correction.

### Benchmark safety

- `just validate` uses non-recording `bench-check`.
- Do not run or commit recording benchmark output unless performance history is
  intentionally being updated.
- A benchmark fluctuation does not replace correctness evidence.
- Generated benchmark history is outside this standards split.

### Failure handling

- Do not ignore or suppress a failed required gate.
- Do not remove tests merely to make validation pass.
- Do not use lint allowances without documented justification.
- If a required command fails for environmental reasons, report the exact
  command, failure, completed checks and remaining uncertainty.
- Do not claim full validation when only targeted commands or the
  documentation-only gate ran.

### Code-bearing completion checklist

Before declaring a non-trivial code-bearing slice complete, check:

- Rust source was formatted where applicable.
- The changed code follows `style-guide.bd`.
- Test selection and assertions follow `testing.bd`.
- Relevant architecture boundaries were reviewed.
- Diagnostics remain structured and stage appropriate.
- The progress matrix was reviewed and updated when status changed.
- Documentation was rebuilt when required.
- Generated output was not edited manually.
- Benchmark history was not changed accidentally.
- `just validate` passes.

### Documentation-only completion checklist

Before declaring a documentation-only slice complete, check:

- The changed-file list contains documentation only.
- The documentation release build succeeds.
- Changed routes, links, tables and examples were inspected.
- Generated output was produced from source changes.
- No generated HTML was edited manually.
- No code, test, build, library, manifest, script, benchmark or configuration
  file changed.
